Steady state emission spectra of aqueous PSS-CQD suspension (0.01 wt %) were recorded at various excitation wavelengths (290–400 nm) (Fig. 3b). Excitation-dependent emission properties were observed with the appearance of two FL bands with maxima located at ∼385 and ∼460 nm (Fig. 3b). We designate these FL bands as B1 (Intrinsic) & B2 (Extrinsic) respectively. According to literature reports, B1 is associated with extended conjugation of π-electron domain present in CQDs [3,16]. The strong emission at B2 has been designated to the presence of surface trap states [8]. Fig. 3b shows both B1 & B2 appear upon exciting the PSS-CQDs at lower excitation wavelengths (270–310 nm). Beyond 340 nm excitation, B2 emission is predominate (Fig. 3b) and the FL band shows maxima emission upon 360 nm excitation. The band intensity is shown to gradually decrease along with a red-shift as excitation shifts to higher wavelengths (Fig. 3b). Fluorescence excitation spectra (FES) at 385 and 460 nm corresponding to B1 and B2 emission were recorded (Fig. 4
                        ). FES spectrum corresponding to B1 was centered ∼270 nm and may correspond to π–π* transition in CQDs [8,25] FES centered at 360 nm, corresponding to B2, is almost mirror image of B2. This indicates that the absorbing and emitting species corresponding to B2 band have similar vibronic energy gaps [25]. Both the FES bands observed can be related to the bands observed in DRS (Fig. 2a). There was no band ∼400 nm in the FES of dilute samples. Interestingly, concentrated PSS-CQDs (>0.1%) showed a new FES band ∼410 nm along with the 360 nm band observed in dilute samples (Fig. 5
                        ). Concentration dependent studies revealed B2 band intensity gradually increased at lower CQD concentrations (Fig. S3). Fig. 5 shows the B2 and FES band are mirror images at 0.05%. Emission spectra recorded at 0.1% PSS-CQD shows a gradual decrease in B2 band intensity possibly due to inner-filter effect based self-quenching as observed in case of fluorescent organic dyes [49].. At higher concentrations (>0.1 wt %), gradual quenching of B2 band was observed. The corresponding FES bands showed slight red-shift along with the appearance of a new low energy band at ∼410 nm (Fig. 5). The phenomenon of appearance of low energy states resulting in red-shift in excitation maxima. It has similarities with the behavior of surface plasmon band of gold nanoparticles (GNPs). When GNPs aggregate or assemble in a medium, a new band is formed or the original SPR band broadens with a red-shift in band-maxima [50,51]. The phenomenon may be attributed to near-field effect and explained in the light of Mie theory [50]. Mie theory states that, as two nanoparticles approach to close proximity, new energy levels are created that minimize the band energy. Beyond 0.3%, the PSS-CQD suspension becomes intensely dark which limits the FL spectral characterization within the standard set up. The onset of FL-quenching and the appearance of the new FES band start at the same concentration range.
